text_Original: I still remember the former CTO of Rift-Oculus came to our university and offered a series of classes about VR. I was fortunate to have taken two of them. I can still recall how primitive the rendering I made in the VR class was at that time. I am surprised at the advancement today but I can still see some problems in this interaction form. First, there are no rendering in the scenes (completely dark). I guess mostly because the facial construction took too many polygons and expensive to render, there is no computation budget to render the rest of the scene with similar levels of details ! Second, the interaction is mostly static. You don't move your body, and you don't see the latency of rendering in the surroundings, this two combines should greatly reduce your dizziness. However, to move to the next level of scene rendering, it might still require a big advancement on the computation ability from the chips..

text_Original: What Mark doesn't seem to care about is how this kind of technology is driving people mad. He uses words like "compelling" or "interesting", but what about the fact that, not only is privacy dead, but a person's boundaries can be completely violated with ease. In the simplest example, you can already take a picture of anyone, and a sample of their voice, and then create a video of them talking, and you can have them say whatever you want to with a script that you create. In the future, you will be able to do the same kind of thing with any girl you choose, but not only will you be able to create a photo realistic video with her face and her voice saying what you want her to, but you will also be able to get her to have sexual interactions with you, in a photo realistic Metaverse environment. Once you're not just wearing a face mask or glasses, but sensors all over your body, you will be able to do whatever you want to do with whoever you want to do it with. Am I the only one who can imagine where this is going? üôÑ
